Mid-term Progress Presentation

Data Science Project

Cheuk Hang Ng

29/7/2022

The project

  • Dataset: 3700 storms occured in Atlantic Ocean between 1979 and 2015

  • Aims:

    • Explore the dataset: exploratory data analysis

    • Model the strength, presence or absence of storms

    • Study rapid intensification

    • Predict rapid intensification of storms

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

The objective of EDA:

  • Uncover the underlying structure of the dataset

  • Find interesting relations among the variables

  • Detect outliers or anomalous instances

Why is it important?

-> Understand patterns within data

-> Choosing appropriate statistical models or machine learning methods

The data

3700 storm instances, maximum of 400 records

  1. Day
  2. Hour
  3. Month
  4. Year
  5. Longitude
  6. Latitude
  7. Wind speed
  8. Potential speed
  9. Pressure
  10. Wind shear

The variables

Initially, the data have different shapes and are needed to be cleaned before we carry out the EDA.

For example, the day dataset:

Data cleaning

Dimensions of dataframes

The first step is to unify the shapes of our data.

## [1] "Shape of day dataframe before: "
## [1]  400 3700
## [1] "Shape of pressure dataframe before: "
## [1] 3700  400
## [1] "Shape of day dataframe after: "
## [1] 3700  400
## [1] "Shape of pressure dataframe after: "
## [1] 3700  400

Null values

We use NA (null value symbol in R) to replace the zeros in the dataset. Although it will lead to some information loss, it is worth to do so as we can separate the real data and null values.

Functions for data cleaning

We defined some handy functions that would help us during the data cleaning process

Longitude degree transformation

Transforming the longitude data so that the values are ranged from -180 degree to 180 degree

#for longitude, we modify the value so that the range is [-180, 180]
degree <- function(x){
    ifelse(x > 180 , x - 360 , x)
}

longitude <- setDT(as.data.frame(sapply(longitude, degree)))

Summary function

This function is used to statistically summarise a variable to a dataframe with arguments chosen from mode, minimum, maximum, mean (or average), standard deviation, first quartile, third quartile, median (or second quartile) or range.

#sample snippet of the function
get_stat <- function(x, ...){
    ...
    for (i in list(...)){
        if (tolower(i) == "mode"){
            col <- apply(x, 1, mfv, na_rm = TRUE)
            col <- sapply(col, "[[", 1)
            name = paste0(deparse(substitute(x)), "_", i)
            result_df[name] <- col
        }
        ...
    ...
    return (result_df)
}

Filter function

This function filters a dataframe with condition(s) on columns and returns a list of storm IDs which fulfill the condition(s)

get_ID <- function(df, column, op, value, ...){
  arguments <- list(...)
  f <- match.fun(match.arg(op, choices = c('<', '>', '==', '>=', '<=')))
  ...
  else if {
    df %>%
    add_rownames() %>%
    filter(f(!!sym(column),value)) -> temp
    for(i in seq(from=1, to=length(arguments), by=3)){
      f <- match.fun(match.arg(arguments[[i+1]], choices = c('<', '>', '==', '>=', '<=')))
       
      temp %>%
      filter(f(!!sym(arguments[[i]]), arguments[[i+2]])) -> temp
    }
    temp %>%
    `[[`("rowname") %>%
    as.numeric() -> output 
    return (output)
  }
}

Exploratory data analysis

Correlation plot

A correlation plot can be used as a general guide on the relationships between variables, with visualised strength of correlations.

Data visualisation

Univariate data visualisation

Wind speed and pressure being the major features of a storm, it is worth to explore their relationship

Data visualisation

By plotting the extrema of these two variables, we obtained a linearly inversed relation.

Data visualisation

We are also interested in the strength as well as the life time of storms by month.

Storms with high maximum wind speed and high average wind speed are occurred mostly between July and October.

Data visualisation

The distribution of life time of storms is similar to that of average/ maximum wind speed.

Data visualisation

A weak proportionate relation is observed between duration, average wind speed and wind speed range.

Storm tracks visulisation

We randomly picked 100 storms from the dataset and visualised their tracks:

No clear pattern is found.

Storms clustering and clustered EDA

Using algorithms to cluster the storms is a good way to analyse the dataset.

It helps us to identify storms that behave similarly.

K-means clustering

At this stage, we applied k-means algorithm to cluster the storms.

  • Easy to apply

  • Easy to visualise

Choice of number of clusters

Good clustering result depends on the choice of number of clusters when using k-means algorithm.

We can see that the decreasing rate of the loss function started to fall when k = 3. By the Elbow method, we chose 3 to be the number of clusters.

Choice of number of cluster

From the cluster plot, we can see that when k = 3 the boundaries are quite clear.

Data visualization by cluster

Group 1 stands out from the rests by having relatively high average wind speed (> 40) and low average pressure (< 995).

Data visualization by cluster

We can see that group 1 storms have greater maximum wind speed and smaller minimum pressure, but the maximum pressure to minimum wind speed ratios are similar for all three clusters.

Data visualization by cluster

Another variable that differs the clusters.

Data visualization by cluster

Data visualization by cluster

Group 2 storms have slightly longer life time than group 3.
